```

**7. Custom Alert Mechanism**:
```java
@Component
public class ErrorRateMonitor {
    private int errorCount = 0;
    private final AlertService alertService;

    @Scheduled(fixedRate = 60000)  // Every minute
    public void checkErrorRate() {
        if (errorCount >= 5) {  // 5 errors in a minute
            alertService.sendAlert("High 500 error rate: " + errorCount + " errors");
            errorCount = 0;
        }
    }

    public void incrementErrorCount() {
        errorCount++;
    }
}
```

**Complete Setup Stack**:
- **Monitoring**: Prometheus/Grafana
- **Logging**: ELK (Elasticsearch, Logstash, Kibana) or Splunk
- **Alerting**: Prometheus AlertManager
- **Notifications**: Slack, PagerDuty, Email
- **Metrics**: Micrometer

This multi-layered approach ensures comprehensive visibility into production errors.

Partial failures occur when some microservices succeed while others fail. Handling requires compensating transactions, retries, and fallbacks:

**1. Circuit Breaker Pattern**:
```java
@Service
public class PaymentService {
    @CircuitBreaker(name = "paymentService", fallbackMethod = "fallbackPay")
    public PaymentResponse processPayment(PaymentRequest request) {
        return paymentClient.charge(request);
    }

    public PaymentResponse fallbackPay(PaymentRequest request, Exception ex) {
        // Return cached response or queue for retry
        return PaymentResponse.builder()
            .status("PENDING")
            .message("Payment queued for retry")
            .build();
    }
}
```

**2. Saga Pattern - Orchestration Based**:
```java
@Service
public class OrderSaga {

    public void executeOrder(OrderRequest request) {
        try {
            // Step 1: Reserve inventory
            inventoryService.reserve(request.getItems());

            // Step 2: Process payment
            paymentService.charge(request.getPayment());

            // Step 3: Create shipment
            shippingService.createShipment(request.getAddress());

        } catch (PaymentException e) {
            // Compensate: rollback previous steps
            inventoryService.release(request.getItems());
            throw new OrderFailedException("Payment failed", e);
        } catch (ShippingException e) {
            // Compensate for payment and inventory
            paymentService.refund(request.getPayment());
            inventoryService.release(request.getItems());
            throw new OrderFailedException("Shipping failed", e);
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Saga Pattern - Event Based (Better for Distributed Systems)**:
```java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    @Autowired
    private KafkaTemplate<String, OrderEvent> kafkaTemplate;

    @PostMapping("/orders")
    public ResponseEntity<Order> createOrder(@RequestBody OrderRequest request) {
        Order order = orderRepository.save(new Order(request));
        kafkaTemplate.send("order.created", new OrderCreatedEvent(order.getId()));
        return ResponseEntity.ok(order);
    }
}

@Service
public class InventoryService {
    @KafkaListener(topics = "order.created")
    public void handleOrderCreated(OrderCreatedEvent event) {
        try {
            inventoryRepository.reserve(event.getOrderId());
            kafkaTemplate.send("inventory.reserved", new InventoryReservedEvent(event.getOrderId()));
        } catch (Exception e) {
            kafkaTemplate.send("order.failed", new OrderFailedEvent(event.getOrderId()));
        }
    }
}

@Service
public class PaymentService {
    @KafkaListener(topics = "inventory.reserved")
    public void handleInventoryReserved(InventoryReservedEvent event) {
        try {
            processPayment(event.getOrderId());
            kafkaTemplate.send("payment.completed", new PaymentCompletedEvent(event.getOrderId()));
        } catch (Exception e) {
            // Publish compensation event
            kafkaTemplate.send("inventory.rollback", new RollbackEvent(event.getOrderId()));
        }
    }
}

@Service
public class RollbackService {
    @KafkaListener(topics = "inventory.rollback")
    public void handleRollback(RollbackEvent event) {
        inventoryRepository.release(event.getOrderId());
    }
}
```

**4. Retry with Exponential Backoff**:
```java
@Service
public class ResilientService {

    @Retry(maxAttempts = 3, delay = 1000, multiplier = 2.0)
    public void callExternalAPI() {
        // Will retry on failure with exponential backoff
        // 1s, 2s, 4s delays
        externalAPI.call();
    }
}
```

**5. Timeout Pattern**:
```java
@Service
public class TimeoutExample {

    @Timeout(value = 5000)
    public Response callWithTimeout() {
        // Fails if takes > 5 seconds
        return slowService.call();
    }
}
```

**6. Bulkhead Pattern - Isolate Failures**:
```java
@Service
public class IsolatedService {

    // Separate thread pool for payment operations
    @Bulkhead(name = "payment", value = 5)
    public PaymentResponse processPayment(PaymentRequest request) {
        return paymentService.process(request);
    }

    // Separate thread pool for shipping operations
    @Bulkhead(name = "shipping", value = 10)
    public ShippingResponse processShipping(ShippingRequest request) {
        return shippingService.process(request);
    }
}
```

**7. Idempotency for Safe Retries**:
```java
@PostMapping("/payments")
public ResponseEntity<PaymentResponse> makePayment(
        @RequestHeader("Idempotency-Key") String idempotencyKey,
        @RequestBody PaymentRequest request) {

    // Check if already processed
    Optional<PaymentResponse> existing =
        paymentRepository.findByIdempotencyKey(idempotencyKey);
    if (existing.isPresent()) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(existing.get());
    }

    // Process payment
    PaymentResponse response = processPayment(request);
    paymentRepository.save(response, idempotencyKey);

    return ResponseEntity.ok(response);
}
```

**Best Practices**:
1. Use Circuit Breaker to prevent cascading failures
2. Implement Saga pattern for distributed transactions
3. Use idempotent operations for safe retries
4. Implement bulkhead pattern to isolate failures
5. Log all compensation events for debugging
6. Use dead-letter queues for failed events

Logging all @Transactional methods requires AOP (Aspect-Oriented Programming) to intercept method calls:

**Solution 1: Using Spring AOP Aspect**:
```java
@Aspect
@Component
public class TransactionLoggingAspect {

    private static final Logger logger =
        LoggerFactory.getLogger(TransactionLoggingAspect.class);

    // Pointcut to match all @Transactional methods
    @Pointcut("@annotation(org.springframework.transaction.annotation.Transactional)")
    public void transactionalMethods() {}

    // Before method execution
    @Before("transactionalMethods()")
    public void logTransactionStart(JoinPoint joinPoint) {
        String methodName = joinPoint.getSignature().getName();
        String className = joinPoint.getTarget().getClass().getSimpleName();
        Object[] args = joinPoint.getArgs();

        logger.info("TRANSACTION START: {}.{} with args: {}",
            className, methodName, Arrays.toString(args));
    }

    // After successful execution
    @AfterReturning(pointcut = "transactionalMethods()", returning = "result")
    public void logTransactionSuccess(JoinPoint joinPoint, Object result) {
        String methodName = joinPoint.getSignature().getName();
        String className = joinPoint.getTarget().getClass().getSimpleName();

        logger.info("TRANSACTION COMMITTED: {}.{} returned: {}",
            className, methodName, result);
    }

    // After exception
    @AfterThrowing(pointcut = "transactionalMethods()", throwing = "exception")
    public void logTransactionRollback(JoinPoint joinPoint, Exception exception) {
        String methodName = joinPoint.getSignature().getName();
        String className = joinPoint.getTarget().getClass().getSimpleName();

        logger.error("TRANSACTION ROLLED BACK: {}.{} due to: {}",
            className, methodName, exception.getMessage(), exception);
    }
}
```

**Solution 2: Advanced - Log with Propagation Details**:
```java
@Aspect
@Component
public class AdvancedTransactionLoggingAspect {

    private static final Logger logger =
        LoggerFactory.getLogger(AdvancedTransactionLoggingAspect.class);

    @Around("@annotation(transactional)")
    public Object logTransactionalMethod(ProceedingJoinPoint pjp,
            Transactional transactional) throws Throwable {

        String methodName = pjp.getSignature().getName();
        String className = pjp.getTarget().getClass().getSimpleName();

        // Log transaction configuration
        logger.info("TX_START: {}.{} | Propagation: {} | Isolation: {}",
            className, methodName,
            transactional.propagation(),
            transactional.isolation());

        long startTime = System.currentTimeMillis();

        try {
            Object result = pjp.proceed();
            long duration = System.currentTimeMillis() - startTime;

            logger.info("TX_COMMIT: {}.{} | Duration: {}ms",
                className, methodName, duration);

            return result;

        } catch (Exception ex) {
            long duration = System.currentTimeMillis() - startTime;

            logger.error("TX_ROLLBACK: {}.{} | Duration: {}ms | Error: {}",
                className, methodName, duration, ex.getMessage(), ex);

            throw ex;
        }
    }
}
```

**Solution 3: Method-Level Annotation Inspection**:
```java
@Aspect
@Component
public class DetailedTransactionLoggingAspect {

    @Before("transactionalMethods()")
    public void logBeforeTransaction(JoinPoint joinPoint) {
        MethodSignature signature = (MethodSignature) joinPoint.getSignature();
        Method method = signature.getMethod();

        // Get @Transactional annotation
        Transactional txAnnotation = method.getAnnotation(Transactional.class);

        logger.info("TX Start - Method: {} | Propagation: {} | ReadOnly: {} | Timeout: {}s",
            method.getName(),
            txAnnotation.propagation(),
            txAnnotation.readOnly(),
            txAnnotation.timeout());
    }
}
```

**Configuration to Enable AOP Aspects**:
```java
@Configuration
@EnableAspectJAutoProxy  // Enable AOP proxy creation
public class AopConfig {
    // This enables the aspects to work
}
```

**Usage Example**:
```java
@Service
public class OrderService {

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED)
    public Order createOrder(OrderRequest request) {
        // Business logic
        return orderRepository.save(new Order(request));
    }

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW, readOnly = false)
    public void updateOrderStatus(Long orderId, OrderStatus status) {
        Order order = orderRepository.findById(orderId).orElseThrow();
        order.setStatus(status);
        orderRepository.save(order);
    }
}
```

**Expected Log Output**:
```
INFO: TX_START: OrderService.createOrder | Propagation: REQUIRED | Isolation: DEFAULT
INFO: TX_COMMIT: OrderService.createOrder | Duration: 125ms
INFO: TX_START: OrderService.updateOrderStatus | Propagation: REQUIRES_NEW
INFO: TX_COMMIT: OrderService.updateOrderStatus | Duration: 89ms
```

**Key Points**:
1. @Aspect marks the class as an AOP aspect
2. @Pointcut defines which methods to intercept
3. @Before/@After/@Around control execution timing
4. MethodSignature provides metadata access
5. Can extract Transactional annotation for full details

Multiple Kafka consumer instances need to be coordinated to avoid duplicate processing. This is handled through **Consumer Groups**:

**Core Concept - Consumer Groups**:
Each consumer instance joins the same consumer group. Kafka automatically partitions messages so each consumer processes a unique set of partitions.

**Configuration**:
```yaml
# application.yml
spring:
  kafka:
    consumer:
      group-id: order-processing-group  # CRITICAL: Same for all instances
      max-poll-records: 100
      session-timeout-ms: 30000
```

```java
@SpringBootApplication
public class KafkaConsumerApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(KafkaConsumerApp.class, args);
    }
}

@Service
public class OrderConsumer {

    @KafkaListener(topics = "orders", groupId = "order-processing-group")
    public void processOrder(OrderEvent event) {
        // Only ONE instance processes each message
        // Multiple instances share the load
        System.out.println("Processing: " + event);
    }
}
```

**Scenario: Ensuring Single Processing (NOT load distribution)**:

If you need ONLY one instance to process ALL messages (not distribute):

```java
@Service
public class SingleInstanceProcessor {

    @KafkaListener(
        topics = "critical-events",
        groupId = "single-processor",
        concurrency = "1"  // Only one thread processes
    )
    public void processExclusively(CriticalEvent event) {
        // This will be processed by only ONE consumer group
        // across all instances
        criticalService.handle(event);
    }
}
```

**Advanced: Multiple Consumer Groups for Different Processing**:
```java
@Service
public class MultiGroupConsumer {

    // Group 1: Order processing
    @KafkaListener(topics = "orders", groupId = "order-processors")
    public void processOrders(OrderEvent event) {
        orderService.process(event);
    }

    // Group 2: Inventory updates (separate instance can process same event)
    @KafkaListener(topics = "orders", groupId = "inventory-updaters")
    public void updateInventory(OrderEvent event) {
        inventoryService.update(event);
    }
}
```

**Partition Assignment Strategies**:
```yaml
spring:
  kafka:
    consumer:
      group-id: my-group
      partition-assignment-strategy: range  # or 'round-robin', 'sticky'
```

**Handling with Explicit Partitioning**:
```java
@Service
public class PartitionedConsumer {

    @KafkaListener(topics = "orders", groupId = "my-group", topicPartitions = {
        @TopicPartition(topic = "orders", partitions = {0, 1})
    })
    public void listenToPartitions(OrderEvent event) {
        // This instance only listens to partitions 0 and 1
        orderService.process(event);
    }
}
```

**Deployment Architecture**:
```
Kafka Topic: orders (4 partitions)
├── Partition 0
├── Partition 1
├── Partition 2
└── Partition 3

Consumer Group: order-processing-group
├── Instance 1 → processes Partitions [0, 1]
├── Instance 2 → processes Partitions [2, 3]
└── Instance 3 → idle (no assigned partitions)
```

**Critical Properties**:
```java
@Configuration
public class KafkaConsumerConfig {

    @Bean
    public ConsumerFactory<String, OrderEvent> consumerFactory() {
        Map<String, Object> props = new HashMap<>();
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");

        // CRITICAL: All instances must have same group-id
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, "order-processing-group");

        // Concurrency level for threads in single instance
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.CONCURRENCY_HINT, 3);

        // Automatically commit offset after processing
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG, true);
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.AUTO_COMMIT_INTERVAL_MS_CONFIG, 1000);

        // Session timeout - when consumer is considered dead
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.SESSION_TIMEOUT_MS_CONFIG, 30000);

        // Max records per poll
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.MAX_POLL_RECORDS_CONFIG, 100);

        return new DefaultKafkaConsumerFactory<>(props);
    }
}
```

**Rebalancing When Adding/Removing Instances**:
```
Instance 1 joins → Rebalance triggered
├── All consumers stop processing briefly
├── Partitions are redistributed
└── Processing resumes with new assignment
```

**Idempotency for Safe Retries**:
```java
@Service
public class IdempotentOrderConsumer {

    @KafkaListener(topics = "orders", groupId = "order-group")
    public void processOrder(OrderEvent event,
            @Header(KafkaHeaders.RECEIVED_PARTITION_ID) int partition,
            @Header(KafkaHeaders.OFFSET) long offset) {

        // Use partition + offset as unique key for idempotency
        String uniqueKey = partition + "-" + offset;

        if (processedKeys.contains(uniqueKey)) {
            logger.info("Message already processed, skipping");
            return;
        }

        orderService.process(event);
        processedKeys.add(uniqueKey);
    }
}
```

**Key Takeaway**: The magic is in **group-id** - all instances with same group-id automatically coordinate through Kafka's group coordination protocol. Kafka ensures each partition is assigned to only one consumer in the group.

